Slinky Markets is building the prediction layer of the internet, a Solana-powered protocol where belief itself becomes liquid. Speculation is no longer a side effect of the internet; it is the internet. Every cycle, the number of things you can trade multiplies. Tokens, NFTs, points, perps — the line between participation and speculation keeps blurring. You’re no longer just holding assets, you’re holding opinions. And soon, every opinion will have a price. That’s hyperfinancialisation, and it’s inevitable.

Traditional prediction markets were built for a slower world, ones that moved on elections, sports, or macro outcomes that settled over weeks or months. But the internet doesn’t wait. It moves on memes, moments, and minutes. By the time old markets resolve, the culture has already shifted. Attention decays faster than liquidity can catch up, and that’s where Slinky comes in.

Slinky introduces MicroMarkets, short-lived, high-frequency prediction markets designed for the timeline economy. They let anyone trade what’s happening right now, from whether Fartcoin breaks 300m this week to if a Threadguy sells the rest of his Zcash before December. Every moment becomes a market. Every belief becomes a position. Culture turns into collateral, and time becomes the most valuable asset of all.

Slinky also lets anyone take part in building this new world through User Generated Markets. Anyone can submit a market idea, a meme, an event, a narrative, and if it’s accepted after review, they’ll earn 50% of the trading fees it generates. It’s a system that rewards creativity, speed, and cultural instinct. Builders don’t just create markets, they create opportunities.

In this new age, attention is the ultimate form of liquidity. Every eyeball is capital, every reaction is a trade. The modern market doesn’t reward who builds the best tech; it rewards whoever captures the collective heartbeat of the internet. Slinky amplifies that reality, turning speculation into expression and culture into a global economy.

This isn’t a game. It’s the purest form of capitalism ever built, a protocol that turns belief, culture, and attention into liquid assets. Slinky isn’t just another prediction app. It’s the operating system for hyperfinancialised culture, built for the terminally online and powered by $SLINKY.

The future won’t just be witnessed, it will be traded. And it starts here.

Lulu The Ostrich (LULU) is a cryptocurrency token launched on the Solana-based Bags launchpad platform, with transaction fees directed to support Universal Ostrich Farms in Edgewood, British Columbia. Universal Ostrich Farms is a family-run establishment that has raised healthy ostriches for over 30 years and is currently engaged in legal efforts to prevent a cull ordered by the Canadian Food Inspection Agency. The token aims to raise awareness and provide financial support for the farm’s legal and operational expenses.

I just found the first in-game 'digital asset' from South Park called $canadough

In South Park  “Freemium Isn’t Free,” the boys become addicted to a new Canadian mobile game, Terrance and Phillip: Give Us Your Money. 

The game runs on a fake currency called Canadough. Players can earn it slowly by waiting, or buy it instantly with real money. 

As Stan’s obsession grows, his dad discovers that the game was created by the Canadian Minister of Mobile Gaming under the influence of the Canadian Devil, who invented freemium games as a new form of torment: addiction without violence, profit without substance.

Satan later explains that freemium games exploit the same psychological mechanics as gambling — variable rewards, scarcity, and false progress — keeping players trapped in a loop of digital consumption.

By the end, Stan realises his pursuit of Canadough is empty. The episode serves as a sharp satire of modern monetisation, and a prophetic commentary on how digital economies — from in-game currencies to NFTs and crypto — can use the same behavioural hooks.

$canadough ultimately symbolises the illusion of digital wealth: a system that turns greed and addiction into entertainment, where people keep paying for something that never truly had value.

Mother of God… is a rage comic character of a man staring intently at something as he takes his sunglasses off. It can be also used outside of rage comics to express astonishment or disbelief in response to a shocking image or a video. Similar to the colloquial usage of the phrase, the reaction face can be used to either indicate approval or disapproval, depending on the context. When used in the context of rage comics, it is usually preceded by a stick-figure drawing of the same man humming and walking with sunglasses still on.
